# Cycle Detection in Linked List

I'll show you the most elegant approach (Floyd's algorithm) and explain why it works.

## Solution: Floyd's Cycle Detection (Tortoise & Hare)

```javascript
class ListNode {
  constructor(value) {
    this.value = value;
    this.next = null;
  }
}

/**
 * Detects if a linked list contains a cycle
 * @param {ListNode} head - The head of the linked list
 * @returns {boolean} - True if cycle exists, false otherwise
 */
function hasCycle(head) {
  if (!head || !head.next) return false;

  let slow = head;      // Moves 1 step at a time
  let fast = head;      // Moves 2 steps at a time

  while (fast && fast.next) {
    slow = slow.next;
    fast = fast.next.next;

    // If they meet, cycle exists
    if (slow === fast) {
      return true;
    }
  }

  return false;  // No cycle found
}
```

## Why This Works (The Math)

**Core Insight**: If there's a cycle, two pointers moving at different speeds MUST eventually meet.

**Proof**:
- If no cycle exists: `fast` reaches the end (`null`) first
- If cycle exists: 
  - `slow` enters the cycle and stays in it
  - `fast` enters the cycle and catches up to `slow`
  - They move at relative speed 1 (fast gains 1 position per iteration)
  - Eventually: `fast.position ≡ slow.position (mod cycle_length)`

**Example**:
```
List: 1 → 2 → 3 → 4 → 5
              ↑       ↓
              ← ← ← ←

Iteration | Slow | Fast | Same?
    0     |  1   |  1   | ✓ (same start)
    1     |  2   |  3   | ✗
    2     |  3   |  5   | ✗
    3     |  4   |  4   | ✓ CYCLE DETECTED
```

## Bonus: Finding the Cycle Start Node

```javascript
/**
 * Finds the node where the cycle begins
 * @param {ListNode} head
 * @returns {ListNode|null} - The node starting the cycle, or null if no cycle
 */
function detectCycleStart(head) {
  if (!head || !head.next) return null;

  let slow = head;
  let fast = head;

  // Step 1: Detect cycle exists
  while (fast && fast.next) {
    slow = slow.next;
    fast = fast.next.next;
    if (slow === fast) break;
  }

  // No cycle found
  if (!fast || !fast.next) return null;

  // Step 2: Find cycle start
  // When slow and fast meet, slow has traveled: a + b
  // fast has traveled: a + b + c + b = a + 2b + c
  // Since fast = 2*slow: a + 2b + c = 2(a + b)
  // Solving: a = c
  // So, moving one pointer from head and one from meeting point,
  // both move at same speed, they meet at cycle start

  let pointer1 = head;
  let pointer2 = slow;  // Meeting point

  while (pointer1 !== pointer2) {
    pointer1 = pointer1.next;
    pointer2 = pointer2.next;
  }

  return pointer1;  // Cycle start node
}
```

## Complexity Analysis

| Approach | Time | Space | Notes |
|----------|------|-------|-------|
| **Floyd's Algorithm** | O(n) | O(1) | ✅ Optimal |
| Hash Set | O(n) | O(n) | Simple but uses extra space |

### Why O(n) for Floyd's?
- Worst case: pointer travels through entire list + part of cycle
- In a linked list of `n` nodes, maximum distance is < 2n
- Therefore: O(n)

### Space Complexity
- O(1) because we only use two pointers regardless of input size
- Perfect for memory-constrained environments

## Alternative: Hash Set (Simpler Logic)

```javascript
function hasCycleHashSet(head) {
  const visited = new Set();

  while (head) {
    if (visited.has(head)) {
      return true;  // Cycle detected
    }
    visited.add(head);
    head = head.next;
  }

  return false;
}
```

**Trade-off**: Easier to understand but uses O(n) extra space.

## Testing

```javascript
// Test 1: Cycle exists
const node1 = new ListNode(1);
const node2 = new ListNode(2);
const node3 = new ListNode(3);
const node4 = new ListNode(4);

node1.next = node2;
node2.next = node3;
node3.next = node4;
node4.next = node2;  // Creates cycle: 2 → 3 → 4 → 2

console.log(hasCycle(node1));        // true
console.log(detectCycleStart(node1).value);  // 2

// Test 2: No cycle
const head = new ListNode(1);
head.next = new ListNode(2);
head.next.next = new ListNode(3);

console.log(hasCycle(head));  // false
```

## Key Takeaways

✅ **Floyd's Algorithm** is the gold standard (O(n) time, O(1) space)  
✅ The algorithm is **deterministic** — it always works if a cycle exists  
✅ The **meeting point math** is elegant and surprisingly simple  
✅ This technique generalizes to finding cycle length and start position

The beauty of this approach is that it requires zero extra memory while maintaining linear time complexity — a rare combination in computer science!

